Working with a GitHub Repository: Fork or Clone
Option 1: Fork the Repository
Go to the original GitHub repository.
Click the Fork button in the top-right corner.
Select the account or organization to fork into.

Clone the fork locally:

git clone https://github.com/username/forked-repo.git
cd forked-repo

Work on the main branch:

git checkout main
Edit code, run tests, and make changes.

Commit changes:

git add .
git commit -m "Describe changes made"

Push changes to the fork:

git push origin main
GitHub Actions in .github/workflows will run automatically on pushes to main.

(Optional) Keep the fork updated with the original repository:

git remote add upstream https://github.com/original-owner/original-repo.git
git fetch upstream
git merge upstream/main
git push origin main
Option 2: Clone and Create a New Repository
Go to GitHub and create a new empty repository in the account or organization.
Give the repository a name.
Do not initialize with a README, .gitignore, or license.

Clone the original repository locally:

git clone https://github.com/original-owner/original-repo.git
cd original-repo

Connect the local copy to the new repository:

git remote remove origin
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/new-repo.git

Work on the main branch:

git checkout main
Edit code, run tests, and make changes.

Commit changes:

git add .
git commit -m "Describe changes made"

Push changes to the new repository:

git push -u origin main
GitHub Actions in .github/workflows will run automatically if present.

(Optional) Keep the local repository updated with the original repository:

git remote add upstream https://github.com/original-owner/original-repo.git
git fetch upstream
git merge upstream/main
git push origin main
Best Practice Note
Working directly on main is acceptable in personal repositories.
In production or collaborative environments, it is recommended to work on feature branches and merge into main to reduce risk of conflicts or breaking changes.
